// Canopy's WebAssembly Component Model contract.
//
// This `.wit` is the language-neutral description of how an untrusted Canopy guest
// talks to a host — the typed, capability-based protocol expressed in the Component
// Model's type system. It is the interface artifact that a future `wit-bindgen` step
// would consume to generate guest stubs (in Rust, C, JS, Python, Go, …) and a host
// `Linker`. Today it is a spec only; no codegen is wired into the build (see
// wit/README.md).
//
// It mirrors, one-for-one, the runtime contract that `canopy-transport-wasmtime`
// enforces over *core* wasm modules today:
//
//   * The guest's ONLY capability is handing the host a batch of op bytes to apply.
//     In the core-wasm transport that is the single granted import
//     `env::canopy_apply(ptr, len)`; here it is the import `apply: func(ops: list<u8>)`.
//     The Component Model carries the list with an owned length, so there is no raw
//     pointer and no host-side bounds math — the boundary is type-checked.
//   * The host validates every node handle while decoding (a forged handle is
//     rejected), so the bytes are untrusted exactly as in the sandboxed transport.
//   * There is no ambient authority: no WASI, no clock, no filesystem, no network.
//     The guest world below imports *only* `host`, so a guest structurally cannot
//     reach anything else.
//
// The op bytes themselves are the canopy-protocol wire format (the same bytes the
// C ABI and the wasmtime transport carry); the Component Model boundary deliberately
// stays oblivious to their internal structure and ships them as an opaque
// `list<u8>`. That keeps the wire format free to evolve without a WIT change.

package canopy:ui@0.1.0;

/// Canopy-owned handle types and shared records. Handles are opaque integers minted
/// and validated by the host — naming one does not grant access, mirroring the
/// unforgeable-handle guarantee in `canopy-protocol`.
interface types {
    /// Opaque, host-minted node handle. The host arena validates ownership on every
    /// mutating op, so a guest can only ever name a node it was handed. `0` is the
    /// implicit host root.
    type node-id = u64;

    /// Interned-string id. Strings are sent once (inside an op batch) and then
    /// referenced by this id, keeping the hot-path ops tiny.
    type str-id = u32;

    /// Event-handler id, minted guest-side and echoed back in a delivered event so
    /// the guest can route a host->guest event to the right closure.
    type handler-id = u32;

    /// Interned event-kind id (e.g. click / input). Values are assigned by the host
    /// widget registry, not hard-coded here.
    type event-kind = u16;

    /// One host->guest input event, the decoded form of the protocol's
    /// `DispatchEvent` op. The guest receives these through `host.poll-events` and
    /// dispatches them to the handler it registered.
    record event {
        /// The node the event targets (must be one the guest created).
        node: node-id,
        /// What kind of event it is (click, input, …).
        kind: event-kind,
        /// The handler the guest registered for this (node, kind) pair.
        handler: handler-id,
    }

    /// Why an `apply` was rejected. The host never traps the guest for bad ops; it
    /// returns one of these so the guest can react (mirrors `canopy-traits::HostError`
    /// plus the transport's size guard).
    enum apply-error {
        /// An op named a node the guest never created (the capability boundary).
        bad-handle,
        /// The bytes were not a decodable op-stream.
        decode,
        /// The op is unsupported on this host/tier.
        unsupported,
        /// The batch exceeded the host's size cap; it was rejected untouched.
        too-large,
    }
}

/// The single capability the host grants the guest: apply a batch of op bytes, and
/// drain any pending host->guest events. This is the *entire* host surface — there is
/// nothing else to import, which is what makes the guest unable to reach the OS.
interface host {
    use types.{event, apply-error};

    /// Hand the host one batch of canopy-protocol op bytes to validate and apply.
    ///
    /// This is the guest's only way to change the UI. The host decodes the bytes,
    /// validates every node handle (a forged handle => `bad-handle`), and applies the
    /// batch atomically. The `list<u8>` carries its own length, so unlike the raw
    /// `canopy_apply(ptr, len)` core-wasm import there is no untrusted size to
    /// bounds-check by hand — the component boundary does it. On any failure the host
    /// returns the matching `apply-error` instead of trapping the guest.
    apply: func(ops: list<u8>) -> result<_, apply-error>;

    /// Drain pending host->guest input events (clicks, text input, …) that have
    /// accumulated since the last call. Returns them in arrival order; an empty list
    /// means "nothing pending". The guest routes each event to the handler it
    /// registered via an earlier `apply` batch.
    poll-events: func() -> list<event>;
}

/// The world an untrusted Canopy guest plugin targets.
///
/// It imports ONLY `host`, so a conforming guest has no ambient authority: no WASI,
/// no clock, no filesystem, no network — exactly the threat model the wasmtime
/// transport enforces at runtime, here expressed structurally in the component's
/// type. The guest exports a single `run` entry point, matching the real guest's
/// exported `run` function.
world canopy-guest {
    /// The one granted capability: apply op batches and poll for events.
    import host;

    /// The guest entry point the host calls once to build (and start driving) its UI.
    /// Inside `run` the guest emits op batches through `host.apply`; long-lived guests
    /// keep calling `host.poll-events` / `host.apply` to react to input.
    export run: func();
}
